Package opennlp.ccg.realize

Interface Summary
Hypertagger A hypertagger is a realization supertagger.
PruningStrategy Interface for edge pruning strategies.
 

Class Summary
Chart The chart manages the creation of edges.
DiversityPruningStrategy Abstract n-best edge pruning strategy that keeps edges diversified according to the notCompellinglyDifferent equivalence relation.
Edge An edge is a tracker for a sign, ie a sign together with bitsets representing its coverage of the input predicates and the semantic indices used, along with lists of the active LF alts.
EdgeCombos EdgeCombos is a simple data structure that allows a representative edge to collect the info about successful combinations of the edge (with other edges or unary rules) that is needed to create analogous new result edges for edges that share the same category, without having to invoke the combinatory rules.
EdgeFactory The EdgeFactory is responsible for creating edges.
EdgeHash A set of edges, unique up to surface words.
FeatureLicenser The feature licenser is a helper class for the edge factory, responsible for managing features which license the use and instantiation of semantically null or marked categories.
LexicalDiversityPruningStrategy A diversity pruning strategy that defines signs to be notCompellinglyDifferent if the set of open class stems is the same.
NBestPruningStrategy Default, n-best edge pruning strategy.
Realizer The realizer manages the realization process.
RuleInstance A rule instance is a tracker for an instantiated version of a type changing rule, ie a type changing rule with its semantics instantiated together with bitsets representing its coverage of the input predicates and the indices in its arg category, along with lists of the active LF alts.
StemPruningStrategy A diversity pruning strategy that defines signs to be notCompellinglyDifferent if they have the same sequence of stems.
Tracker A tracker is a wrapper for either a sign (ie, an edge) or a type changing rule (ie, a rule instance) which has bitsets for representing the coverage of the input predicates and the semantic indices used.
